WEBVTT

00:07.441 --> 00:08.175
‐ Previously on
"Resident Alien"...

00:09.009 --> 00:09.977
‐ Jay at the clinic.

00:10.010 --> 00:11.512
That's Asta's daughter.

00:11.545 --> 00:12.946
‐ That's a really big secret,
and it's gonna hurt

00:12.980 --> 00:13.981
a lot of people
when it comes out.

00:14.014 --> 00:15.382
‐ Let go!

00:17.718 --> 00:19.353
I thought she'd be better off
without me,

00:19.386 --> 00:20.721
but what if that's not true?

00:20.754 --> 00:21.688
Stop! He's not worth it.

00:21.722 --> 00:22.823
‐ [gasps]

00:22.856 --> 00:24.625
‐ What if she's supposed
to be with me?

00:24.658 --> 00:26.960
‐ I hear they found a body.
‐ No, just a foot.

00:26.994 --> 00:28.262
‐ There's a dead body
out there somewhere,

00:28.295 --> 00:30.063
and we're not gonna rest
until we find it.

00:30.097 --> 00:32.099
[suspenseful music]

00:32.132 --> 00:34.001
‐ My son Max told me
you're an alien.

00:34.034 --> 00:36.169
Frankly,
he is driving me crazy.

00:36.203 --> 00:38.705
‐ I believe you.
I've got a plan.

00:38.739 --> 00:40.140
Hello?

00:40.173 --> 00:42.709
Check this out.
‐ No!

00:42.743 --> 00:44.845
♪ ♪

00:44.878 --> 00:46.046
‐ How did you get in here?

00:46.079 --> 00:48.048
‐ I have a key.

00:48.081 --> 00:50.417
I am still your wife.

00:50.450 --> 00:52.719
♪ ♪

00:52.753 --> 00:55.722
[twangy rock music]

00:55.756 --> 00:57.758
♪ ♪

00:57.791 --> 01:00.694
‐ Harry used the tissue samples
to track back the infection

01:00.727 --> 01:03.430
to the coating on the patient's
artificial aortic valve.

01:03.463 --> 01:05.432
It was amazing work, Harry.
‐ Thank you.

01:05.465 --> 01:07.768
I'm great with the heart
as long as it's not my own.

01:07.801 --> 01:09.236
[all chuckle]

01:09.269 --> 01:12.372
[indistinct chatter]

01:15.576 --> 01:16.877
Uh, excuse me.

01:16.910 --> 01:17.878
‐ Yes, of course.

01:17.911 --> 01:24.885
♪ ♪

01:24.918 --> 01:26.653
‐ Hi, can you help me?
I'm sorry.

01:26.687 --> 01:27.988
‐ Yes.

01:28.021 --> 01:30.891
‐ What do you think
this painting is saying?

01:30.924 --> 01:32.359
‐ Um...

01:32.392 --> 01:34.895
I'm rather trying not
to think about it, actually.

01:34.928 --> 01:37.464
But I'd say...

01:37.497 --> 01:41.468
makes me feel
a bit upside down.

01:41.501 --> 01:43.203
‐ Upside down.

01:43.236 --> 01:44.905
‐ What's it make you feel?

01:44.938 --> 01:46.907
‐ I don't know.
‐ [chuckles]

01:46.940 --> 01:48.875
‐ But I love the mystery.
‐ Mm.

01:48.909 --> 01:50.210
Right.

01:50.243 --> 01:53.246
That's very interesting.

01:53.280 --> 01:55.782
You really ought to share that
interpretation with the artist.

01:55.816 --> 01:57.050
‐ Ah.

01:57.084 --> 01:59.086
‐ Oh. That's me.

01:59.119 --> 02:00.687
Hi, I'm Isabelle.

02:00.721 --> 02:03.123
‐ You're the artist?
‐ I'm the artist. [laughs]

02:03.156 --> 02:04.358
‐ But I thought
you were the waitress.

02:04.391 --> 02:05.926
‐ [whispering]
I'm undercover.

02:05.959 --> 02:07.427
[laughs]

02:07.461 --> 02:09.529
[normal voice] I'll be
the waitress‐‐who will you be?

02:09.563 --> 02:12.265
‐ Uh, I am
the divorced doctor...

02:12.299 --> 02:14.368
‐ Oh.
‐ Who is also undercover.

02:14.401 --> 02:16.103
I'm an art afficionado.

02:17.304 --> 02:18.271
‐ Ah.

02:19.373 --> 02:22.943
As an art afficionado,
what do you say about this?

02:22.976 --> 02:25.012
‐ I love this painting.

02:26.847 --> 02:28.649
‐ Thank you.

02:28.682 --> 02:31.151
‐ I'm Harry Vanderspeigle.

02:31.184 --> 02:33.053
‐ You're Harry Vander‐‐
What's it?

02:33.086 --> 02:35.622
‐ [laughs] Speigle, yes. Yes.
‐ Speigle.

02:35.656 --> 02:38.892
Mm. Unfortunately,
some bastard has outbid you.

02:38.925 --> 02:40.727
‐ A bastard outbid me?

02:40.761 --> 02:42.195
‐ Indeed.
‐ Bastard.

02:42.229 --> 02:44.431
‐ [laughs]
‐ Got to fix that.

02:44.464 --> 02:46.099
Hold on.

02:46.133 --> 02:50.404
$10,000.

02:50.437 --> 02:52.406
I mean, it's for a good cause.

02:52.439 --> 02:53.740
‐ Right.

02:53.774 --> 02:55.942
Indeed.
[giggles]

02:55.976 --> 02:58.345
‐ I'm not letting this
get away.

02:58.378 --> 03:00.213
I want to solve this mystery.

03:00.247 --> 03:03.817
[Nat King Cole's "Nature Boy"]

03:03.850 --> 03:07.521
[inaudible]

03:07.554 --> 03:11.558
‐ ♪ There was a boy ♪

03:11.591 --> 03:16.730
♪ A very strange,
enchanted boy ♪

03:16.763 --> 03:20.333
♪ They say
he wandered very far ♪

03:20.367 --> 03:22.869
♪ Very far ♪

03:22.903 --> 03:27.808
♪ Over land and sea ♪

03:27.841 --> 03:30.811
[romantic music]

03:30.844 --> 03:37.751
♪ ♪

03:42.255 --> 03:45.959
[Brown Bird's "Bilgewater"]

03:45.992 --> 03:49.029
[laidback acoustic strumming]

03:49.062 --> 03:52.299
♪ ♪

03:52.332 --> 03:54.301
‐ Humans
have a strange practice

03:54.334 --> 03:56.570
they call
"the art of bullshitting,"

03:56.603 --> 04:00.207
and that little bastard Max
is Michelangelo.

04:00.240 --> 04:02.209
I hate that kid.

04:02.242 --> 04:04.277
You want to pretend
to be my friend

04:04.311 --> 04:07.247
to steal my keys
and break into my cabin?

04:07.280 --> 04:08.882
Fine with me.

04:08.915 --> 04:12.219
Nice knowing you, friend.

04:12.252 --> 04:13.487
‐ What?

04:15.455 --> 04:17.624
[indistinct voices]
Hello? Hello?

04:17.657 --> 04:19.092
Hello? Hello?

04:19.126 --> 04:20.360
Hello? H‐‐

04:20.393 --> 04:21.661
‐ Max!
[Ben sighs]

04:21.695 --> 04:24.297
Oh, thank God,
you were in here.

04:24.331 --> 04:26.800
‐ [sighs]
‐ You didn't check the closet?

04:26.833 --> 04:28.335
‐ For our sleeping son?

04:28.368 --> 04:31.204
No, I didn't check the closet
or the sock drawers.

04:31.238 --> 04:33.673
‐ He camps out
in here sometimes.

04:33.707 --> 04:35.408
Oh, you must have
fallen asleep.

04:35.442 --> 04:36.977
Come here.
‐ Yeah.

04:37.010 --> 04:38.745
I must have fallen asleep.

04:38.779 --> 04:40.080
[tense music]

04:40.113 --> 04:41.414
No!

04:43.917 --> 04:46.620
[doorbell rings]

04:46.653 --> 04:47.988
‐ All right, now, I'm gonna
need to know

04:48.021 --> 04:49.089
the boy's blood type,

04:49.122 --> 04:50.290
and I'm gonna need
a hair sample.

04:50.323 --> 04:52.192
We gonna hope for the best
but be prepared for the worst.

04:52.225 --> 04:54.094
Now, Deputy, you go up, and you
dust his room for prints.

04:54.127 --> 04:56.096
Now, tell me,
when was the last time

04:56.129 --> 04:57.497
you saw the boy alive?

04:57.531 --> 04:59.666
‐ Well, so, funny story
about Max.

04:59.699 --> 05:00.901
Um...

05:00.934 --> 05:02.435
‐ He was in the closet.

05:02.469 --> 05:03.904
‐ Are you kidding me?

05:03.937 --> 05:06.306
Shit, I scraped ice
off the truck for this?

05:06.339 --> 05:08.108
‐ Actually, I scraped the ice.

05:08.141 --> 05:09.810
‐ Yeah, we're really sorry
to drag you out here.

05:09.843 --> 05:12.112
‐ Then I warmed up the car
while he finished his coffee.

05:12.145 --> 05:13.480
‐ Look, you might want
to tie a rope

05:13.513 --> 05:15.115
around your boy
so you don't lose him.

05:15.148 --> 05:16.316
You know I caught him
riding his bike

05:16.349 --> 05:18.118
way out on Route 16 today?

05:18.151 --> 05:19.653
‐ What? Max, is that true?

05:19.686 --> 05:20.787
‐ You know you're not allowed

05:20.821 --> 05:22.489
to ride your bike
that far from home.

05:22.522 --> 05:23.790
You are grounded for a year.

05:23.824 --> 05:24.758
‐ Honey.
‐ A day?

05:24.791 --> 05:26.927
‐ You can't ground me!
I had a good reason!

05:26.960 --> 05:28.562
‐ [scoffs]
This should be something.

05:28.595 --> 05:30.597
‐ Hey, if my son says
he has a good reason,

05:30.630 --> 05:32.432
he had a good reason.
Go ahead, Max.

05:32.465 --> 05:33.867
‐ Thank you, Mother.

05:33.900 --> 05:36.503
I had to break in
to Dr. Vanderspeigle's house

05:36.536 --> 05:38.305
while he was at work.
‐ Wait, what?

05:38.338 --> 05:39.673
‐ Apology accepted.

05:39.706 --> 05:41.141
‐ What type
of criminal mastermind

05:41.174 --> 05:42.676
are y'all raising
in this house, huh?

05:42.709 --> 05:44.477
‐ I found proof
that he's an alien!

05:44.511 --> 05:45.779
‐ Oh, really?
What kind of proof?

05:45.812 --> 05:49.616
Like, uh, flying orbs
or a loss of, uh...

05:49.649 --> 05:51.151
uh, time.

05:51.184 --> 05:53.153
‐ He has alien technology
in his basement!

05:53.186 --> 05:55.055
‐ Max, you have to stop lying.

05:55.088 --> 05:57.357
‐ I'm not lying!
Sahar was there!

05:57.390 --> 05:59.392
She saw everything!

05:59.426 --> 06:01.328
‐ I don't remember
seeing anything.

06:01.361 --> 06:03.430
‐ What?

06:03.463 --> 06:05.732
‐ I remember
riding bikes, but...

06:05.765 --> 06:08.268
I don't remember going
to the doctor's cabin.

06:09.803 --> 06:11.104
I'm sorry, Max.

06:11.137 --> 06:14.307
[solemn music]

06:14.341 --> 06:17.077
♪ ♪

06:17.110 --> 06:20.046
[soft jazz music
playing on radio]

06:20.080 --> 06:22.549
♪ ♪

06:22.582 --> 06:25.352
‐ You're still here.

06:25.385 --> 06:27.187
You can't wear that.

06:27.220 --> 06:28.955
That is a man's shirt!

06:28.989 --> 06:31.958
‐ I flew across the country
to talk to you,

06:31.992 --> 06:34.194
and you left and drove away.

06:34.227 --> 06:35.929
Where did you go?

06:35.962 --> 06:37.964
‐ To get milk.

06:37.998 --> 06:39.966
‐ So where's the milk?

06:40.000 --> 06:41.434
‐ I drank it.

06:41.468 --> 06:43.069
She's scanning me.

06:43.103 --> 06:44.905
It's a good thing
I didn't murder those kids.

06:44.938 --> 06:46.640
There'd be blood
all over my pants.

06:46.673 --> 06:48.141
And then I'd have
to murder her.

06:48.174 --> 06:50.410
Yes. I made the right choice.

06:50.443 --> 06:52.545
I'm very good at this.

06:52.579 --> 06:54.614
‐ What's different about you?

06:54.648 --> 06:56.416
‐ I shaved my mustache.

06:56.449 --> 06:57.584
‐ You didn't have a mustache.

06:57.617 --> 07:00.420
‐ I grew it,
and then I shaved it...

07:00.453 --> 07:02.756
before I drank the milk.

07:02.789 --> 07:04.758
‐ Are you high?

07:04.791 --> 07:06.826
‐ Yes.

07:06.860 --> 07:10.363
I am high
on the skunk's...weed.

07:10.397 --> 07:14.100
‐ I'm very cross with you.

07:14.134 --> 07:16.536
‐ You sound like James Bond.

07:16.569 --> 07:18.438
[imitating accent]
Very cross with you.

07:18.471 --> 07:20.240
I'm very cross with you.

07:20.273 --> 07:23.376
‐ I was ready to sign
the divorce papers,

07:23.410 --> 07:26.980
and then you stonewalled
the lawyers for months.

07:27.013 --> 07:30.450
Phone calls, emails, texts,
all unanswered.

07:30.483 --> 07:31.952
I don't know if you saw
any of them.

07:31.985 --> 07:34.354
This has been absolute
emotional torture.

07:34.387 --> 07:35.522
If you're ready
to have a divorce,

07:35.555 --> 07:37.257
just sign the papers!

07:37.290 --> 07:38.525
‐ Thank you.

07:41.261 --> 07:42.595
‐ Um...

07:42.629 --> 07:44.531
wow, that was so easy for you.

07:44.564 --> 07:48.001
‐ There's a motel at Exit 42.

07:48.034 --> 07:50.603
‐ And there's an asshole
in the living room.

07:50.637 --> 07:53.473
[somber music]

07:53.506 --> 07:54.708
♪ ♪

07:54.741 --> 07:59.179
I thought we could at least
talk about this like humans.

07:59.212 --> 08:02.849
‐ That's where I sleep.

08:02.882 --> 08:05.051
Ah. Hmm.

08:09.255 --> 08:11.291
[door opens]

08:11.324 --> 08:14.294
[mischievous music]

08:14.327 --> 08:20.900
♪ ♪

08:24.337 --> 08:26.573
‐ What's happening here?

08:26.606 --> 08:28.241
She agreed
to end the relationship;

08:28.274 --> 08:30.677
I've got it in writing.

08:30.710 --> 08:33.013
Don't move.
Don't make a sound.

08:33.046 --> 08:36.316
Just play dead,
and maybe she'll let go.

08:36.349 --> 08:38.852
Actually, this isn't bad.

08:38.885 --> 08:42.322
She's warm,
like a giant ham.

08:42.355 --> 08:45.225
Maybe I can sleep after all.

08:45.258 --> 08:48.395
[Isabelle snoring]

08:50.096 --> 08:51.464
Shit.

08:54.401 --> 08:54.768
[suspenseful music]

08:56.336 --> 08:57.470
‐ [gasps]

08:57.504 --> 08:59.472
‐ Morning, love.

08:59.506 --> 09:01.608
‐ What time is it?
The alarm...

09:01.641 --> 09:03.309
‐ Oh, I turned it off.

09:03.343 --> 09:05.178
I thought
we could use the rest.

09:05.211 --> 09:06.980
[chuckles]

09:07.013 --> 09:08.782
[grunts]

09:08.815 --> 09:11.117
‐ I have to go.
‐ What? When are we gonna talk?

09:11.151 --> 09:12.852
‐ We just did.

09:12.886 --> 09:15.321
Now I have to go to my job.

09:15.355 --> 09:18.324
‐ Since when have you
got a job in Patience?

09:18.358 --> 09:20.060
‐ The town doctor was murdered.

09:20.093 --> 09:24.931
Now I am the town doctor
because I am alive.

09:24.964 --> 09:27.067
‐ You've abandoned
your practice back home,

09:27.100 --> 09:30.170
and now you're in Colorado
playing Dr. Fix‐It?

09:30.203 --> 09:33.339
‐ They just call me
Dr. Vanderspeigle.

09:33.373 --> 09:34.507
Goodbye.

09:36.076 --> 09:39.079
Before you go home,
take out the trash.

09:39.112 --> 09:40.680
I recycle.

09:43.116 --> 09:45.318
[door opens, closes]

09:45.351 --> 09:47.020
I am angry.

09:47.053 --> 09:49.289
I was supposed to be up early
and already on the mountain

09:49.322 --> 09:50.924
to search for my device.

09:50.957 --> 09:52.859
That woman is a distraction.

09:52.892 --> 09:54.794
Why do these creatures
choose to spend their lives

09:54.828 --> 09:56.262
with someone else?

09:56.296 --> 09:58.298
It's bad enough
they're already tethered

09:58.331 --> 09:59.766
to each other through family.

09:59.799 --> 10:01.835
My people do family
the right way.

10:01.868 --> 10:04.804
We don't care
if they live or die.

10:04.838 --> 10:07.574
‐ Take one white one
and one red one with your eggs.

10:07.607 --> 10:10.243
‐ Is that what they call
these yellow things?

10:10.276 --> 10:13.279
Looks like Big Bird exploded
on this plate.

10:13.313 --> 10:14.514
[chuckles]

10:14.547 --> 10:15.949
Wasn't for you, we'd be eating

10:15.982 --> 10:18.952
those half‐smoke sausages
at Bee‐Bee's.

10:18.985 --> 10:21.754
‐ Yeah, I know,
it's not exactly D. C., but...

10:21.788 --> 10:23.723
the mountain air out here
is good for you.

10:23.756 --> 10:26.726
‐ Oh, is that what
we're going with?

10:26.759 --> 10:28.795
Is that why we're here?

10:28.828 --> 10:32.132
Yeah, blame moving out here
on me,

10:32.165 --> 10:35.101
just like you blame me
for everything else.

10:35.135 --> 10:38.538
Probably my fault
Sam got killed, too.

10:39.606 --> 10:41.741
You crack that one yet,
Mikey?

10:44.310 --> 10:46.746
Didn't think so.
[scoffs]

10:46.779 --> 10:49.816
Looks like Sam chose
the wrong town to die in.

10:49.849 --> 10:51.217
‐ You just‐‐
[silverware clatters]

10:51.251 --> 10:52.285
Shit!

10:52.318 --> 10:53.820
‐ What's wrong with you?

10:53.853 --> 10:56.122
And these people trust you
with a gun.

10:56.156 --> 10:57.423
‐ I'm sorry, Dad.

10:57.457 --> 10:59.292
Can you just take
your pills, please?

10:59.325 --> 11:00.860
‐ Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

11:00.894 --> 11:02.195
[sighs]

11:02.228 --> 11:04.864
[clattering, thumping]

11:10.837 --> 11:12.205
‐ Harry!
‐ Huh?

11:12.238 --> 11:14.307
‐ What's going on?
Chasing a raccoon in there?

11:14.340 --> 11:15.909
‐ I'm fine.

11:15.942 --> 11:16.976
[grunts]

11:19.612 --> 11:20.914
There is no racoon.

11:20.947 --> 11:23.183
I'm just putting on my pants.
[zipper closes]

11:23.216 --> 11:24.684
‐ Oh, shit.

11:24.717 --> 11:27.120
Are you living in your truck?

11:27.153 --> 11:29.389
Hey, it's nothing
to be ashamed of.

11:29.422 --> 11:31.457
I‐I sleep at the 59, like,

11:31.491 --> 11:32.892
three nights a week,
so I get it.

11:32.926 --> 11:34.894
‐ I'm not living in my truck.

11:34.928 --> 11:36.462
‐ Oh, I...

11:36.496 --> 11:38.631
I do sleep at the 59.

11:38.665 --> 11:40.466
‐ Is that coffee for me?

11:40.500 --> 11:42.702
‐ Oh, this coffee that I have
not offered to you in any way?

11:42.735 --> 11:44.470
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ No.

11:44.504 --> 11:46.005
‐ Oh.

11:48.041 --> 11:51.044
‐ Anyway, glad I ran into you
because, um...

11:51.077 --> 11:54.480
you know, we had fun,
and we kissed,

11:54.514 --> 11:57.717
which was...interesting.

11:57.750 --> 12:00.820
But I‐I kind of think
we shouldn't drag this whole

12:00.853 --> 12:04.224
"will they, won't they" thing
out more than we need to.

12:05.792 --> 12:07.360
I don't want
to date you anymore.

12:07.393 --> 12:08.461
[groans]

12:08.494 --> 12:10.396
‐ Can I just have a sip?

12:10.430 --> 12:12.632
It will help me move my bowels.
‐ Okay.

12:12.665 --> 12:14.500
No, I can see
that you're hurting,

12:14.534 --> 12:16.169
and I get it.

12:16.202 --> 12:18.171
We can be friends,
I just‐‐it's just‐‐

12:18.204 --> 12:19.973
You're just not my type.

12:20.006 --> 12:22.141
‐ So your type
is not the smartest

12:22.175 --> 12:24.510
and the best person
in the world.

12:24.544 --> 12:25.511
‐ See, there it is.

12:25.545 --> 12:28.314
Uh, I think
it's just your ego.

12:28.348 --> 12:30.516
It's...

12:30.550 --> 12:31.985
I don't even know
how to describe it.

12:32.018 --> 12:33.920
‐ So you're not very smart?

12:35.288 --> 12:37.023
‐ Um...

12:37.056 --> 12:39.092
what the ‐‐‐‐ did you
just say to me?

12:39.125 --> 12:42.161
‐ Oh, no. Human men must not
say mean things to women.

12:42.195 --> 12:46.199
If I don't apologize,
she'll know I'm an alien.

12:46.232 --> 12:47.967
That was mean.

12:48.001 --> 12:50.303
I should not have said that.

12:50.336 --> 12:51.838
‐ Yeah.

12:51.871 --> 12:54.807
‐ I am a man, a human man,
and you are smart,

12:54.841 --> 12:57.076
relative to...

12:57.110 --> 12:58.945
our species.

13:00.446 --> 13:02.148
Goodbye.

13:04.484 --> 13:06.352
‐ Asshole!

13:09.322 --> 13:10.390
‐ Hmm.

13:10.423 --> 13:13.326
[suspenseful music]

13:13.359 --> 13:20.333
♪ ♪

13:24.570 --> 13:28.708
[footsteps descending]

13:44.724 --> 13:47.060
[sniffs]

13:48.594 --> 13:50.897
You lying, cheating bastard.

13:55.568 --> 13:55.968
[suspenseful music]

13:58.171 --> 14:00.273
♪ ♪

14:00.306 --> 14:03.176
[door closes]

14:03.209 --> 14:05.278
‐ Oh, hello, Dr. Vanderspeigle.

14:05.311 --> 14:07.046
I'm surprised
you're still here.

14:07.080 --> 14:09.582
‐ Mayor Hawthorne
hasn't found my replacement yet

14:09.615 --> 14:11.517
because he's bad at his job.

14:11.551 --> 14:13.553
‐ Well, these are
Sam's private medical files.

14:13.586 --> 14:15.688
I thought you might want them.

14:15.722 --> 14:17.190
‐ No.

14:17.223 --> 14:18.858
But okay.

14:18.891 --> 14:20.360
‐ You know, since I'm here,

14:20.393 --> 14:23.329
can I ask if you've finished
Sam's autopsy report?

14:23.363 --> 14:25.264
‐ I can't until I get
the toxicology results

14:25.298 --> 14:26.866
back from the lab in Denver.

14:26.899 --> 14:29.669
‐ So sad to find out
he committed suicide.

14:29.702 --> 14:32.572
‐ Because if he was murdered,
it would not be so sad.

14:32.605 --> 14:34.707
‐ Well, if he
committed suicide,

14:34.741 --> 14:37.977
his insurance claim
would be null and void.

14:38.010 --> 14:42.048
So I'm counting on you, Doctor,
to do the right thing.

14:42.081 --> 14:44.717
You know, you could
use a haircut.

14:44.751 --> 14:46.853
Why don't you come down
to the salon?

14:46.886 --> 14:48.454
I'll cut it for you.

14:48.488 --> 14:50.056
‐ I cut my own hair.

14:50.089 --> 14:52.392
‐ [chuckles]
I see that.

14:52.425 --> 14:54.327
[footsteps departing]

14:54.360 --> 14:55.828
‐ What was that about?

14:55.862 --> 14:57.697
‐ She's pro‐murder.

14:57.730 --> 14:59.665
[dramatic music]

14:59.699 --> 15:03.236
And she wanted you
to take this box

15:03.269 --> 15:06.239
to where the other
dead people boxes go.

15:06.272 --> 15:07.940
‐ Okay, then.

15:10.276 --> 15:13.112
Mrs. Hodges brought this.
I don't know where to put it.

15:13.146 --> 15:14.747
Also, my mom wanted
to thank you

15:14.781 --> 15:16.416
for helping me out
the other night.

15:16.449 --> 15:18.084
She wants
to make you dinner.

15:18.117 --> 15:19.652
‐ Oh. Wow.

15:19.685 --> 15:21.654
That's nice.
She doesn't have to do that.

15:21.687 --> 15:23.656
Um, we can talk about that.

15:23.689 --> 15:26.359
So I'm gonna take this box.

15:26.392 --> 15:28.928
♪ ♪

15:28.961 --> 15:31.197
I have a problem.

15:31.230 --> 15:33.232
‐ So do I.
That box keeps following me.

15:33.266 --> 15:34.700
‐ I messed up.

15:34.734 --> 15:36.335
I never should've
brought Jay here.

15:36.369 --> 15:38.905
She's just so innocent.

15:38.938 --> 15:41.374
Walking around,
not knowing the truth.

15:41.407 --> 15:43.309
‐ Tell her you're her mother.

15:43.342 --> 15:45.545
‐ I gave her up.

15:45.578 --> 15:47.613
I can't just drag her back
now that it suits me.

15:47.647 --> 15:49.449
She has a life and a family.

15:49.482 --> 15:52.485
You know, knowing the truth
should be on her terms

15:52.518 --> 15:53.519
when she's ready.

15:53.553 --> 15:55.321
Jay should not be here.

15:55.354 --> 15:56.956
‐ This is interesting.

15:56.989 --> 15:59.392
She's willing to send Jay away
because she loves her,

15:59.425 --> 16:01.794
not because she hates her.

16:01.828 --> 16:03.095
Fire her.

16:03.129 --> 16:04.497
‐ No.

16:04.530 --> 16:05.798
I can't do that.

16:05.832 --> 16:07.266
‐ Can I?

16:07.300 --> 16:09.068
‐ Although...

16:09.101 --> 16:10.470
her class is almost over.

16:10.503 --> 16:12.672
I could make sure
she gets a good grade.

16:12.705 --> 16:14.340
‐ Harry.

16:14.373 --> 16:15.975
Harry.

16:16.008 --> 16:18.277
Whose scarf is this?

16:18.311 --> 16:20.780
Girl up front?
This woman?

16:20.813 --> 16:23.282
‐ Excuse me.
"This woman"?

16:23.316 --> 16:24.484
Harry, why don't you
tell your girlfriend

16:24.517 --> 16:25.818
that this is a doctor's office

16:25.852 --> 16:28.087
and she cannot barge
into an exam room?

16:28.120 --> 16:29.822
‐ I'm not his girlfriend.

16:29.856 --> 16:31.257
I'm his wife.

16:31.290 --> 16:33.693
‐ His wife?

16:33.726 --> 16:35.361
[scoffs]

16:35.394 --> 16:37.063
Harry here told me
you were dead.

16:37.096 --> 16:38.631
‐ [laughs]
Oh!

16:38.664 --> 16:40.500
‐ [awkwardly]
Ha ha ha...

16:40.533 --> 16:42.802
‐ Do I look dead to you,
Harry?

16:44.170 --> 16:46.772
Would a dead person do this?

16:46.806 --> 16:47.840
Or that?

16:47.874 --> 16:49.842
Ooh, I'm so sorry.
All right, then.

16:49.876 --> 16:51.811
Ooh, and this must be a ghost.

16:51.844 --> 16:53.312
You're dead, too.
I guess we're all dead.

16:53.346 --> 16:54.347
Dead!

16:54.380 --> 16:56.182
♪ ♪

16:56.215 --> 16:58.317
Wow, sorry. Um, right.

16:58.351 --> 16:59.852
You're a monster.

16:59.886 --> 17:02.388
I‐I‐I'm going back
to New York.

17:02.421 --> 17:03.856
I‐I can't.

17:03.890 --> 17:06.759
‐ "Monster" is a cheese, right?

17:08.995 --> 17:10.096
‐ [chuckles]

17:11.998 --> 17:15.334
‐ Can I have a glass
of your driest white, please?

17:15.368 --> 17:16.669
‐ Eeh...

17:16.702 --> 17:18.471
Well, we've been using
the same box of wine

17:18.504 --> 17:21.841
as a stepladder
since Halloween, so...

17:21.874 --> 17:24.210
Uh, whiskey‐‐
that's your best bet.

17:24.243 --> 17:25.378
‐ Oh, dear.

17:25.411 --> 17:27.513
‐ And you're in luck.

17:27.547 --> 17:29.448
Still in time
for the breakfast special,

17:29.482 --> 17:31.217
if you want me
to crack an egg into it.

17:31.250 --> 17:32.752
‐ I am going through a divorce,

17:32.785 --> 17:35.888
but I'm not quite at
"egg in my whiskey" phase yet.

17:35.922 --> 17:38.891
‐ Divorce. That's rough.
I hear ya.

17:38.925 --> 17:40.393
‐ You're divorced?

17:40.426 --> 17:42.228
‐ Oh, no. Not yet, anyway.

17:42.261 --> 17:43.529
You know, someday.

17:43.563 --> 17:45.031
‐ Oh. [laughs]
‐ Yeah.

17:45.064 --> 17:47.567
Still kind of working
on that pre‐divorce part.

17:47.600 --> 17:49.769
‐ Don't bother.

17:49.802 --> 17:51.537
Ah, God. How do people...

17:51.571 --> 17:54.073
Ooh. Wow.

17:54.106 --> 17:55.107
Really sneaks up on you.

17:55.141 --> 17:57.343
‐ Yeah. It's like a stroke.

17:57.376 --> 18:00.580
‐ I just don't understand
how people can change so much.

18:00.613 --> 18:04.417
He used to be
so alive and present,

18:04.450 --> 18:07.286
and now he's, like, blunt.

18:07.320 --> 18:09.288
‐ I know blunt guys.
‐ Mm.

18:09.322 --> 18:10.756
‐ Yeah, the guy I'm dating,
it's like,

18:10.790 --> 18:13.826
he's so direct, you know,
which is refreshing.

18:13.859 --> 18:15.761
It's kind of hot, but...
‐ Mm.

18:15.795 --> 18:18.664
‐ Sometimes it's...
it's really brutal.

18:18.698 --> 18:20.366
‐ Exactly.
God, they're all the same.

18:20.399 --> 18:23.202
‐ Probably dating the same guy.
‐ Maybe there's two of them.

18:23.235 --> 18:25.438
‐ [laughing]
Can you imagine?

18:25.471 --> 18:29.408
[telephone rings,
indistinct chatter]

18:29.442 --> 18:30.576
‐ [gasps]

18:31.944 --> 18:34.180
I'm sorry.
I thought you were my wife.

18:34.213 --> 18:36.849
‐ Max has something
he would like to tell you.

18:38.184 --> 18:39.218
Go ahead, Max.

18:40.686 --> 18:42.521
‐ I stole your keys
and made a copy of them

18:42.555 --> 18:44.223
to sneak into your cabin.

18:44.256 --> 18:45.658
‐ What?

18:45.691 --> 18:48.961
I am horrified
at this accusation!

18:48.995 --> 18:51.497
‐ Oh, no, he didn't accuse you
of anyth‐‐

18:51.530 --> 18:53.899
‐ I don't accept your apology!

18:53.933 --> 18:55.601
‐ Well, he hasn't
apologized yet.

18:55.635 --> 18:57.269
‐ I'm getting ahead of myself.

18:57.303 --> 18:58.871
‐ Max. Go on.

19:00.306 --> 19:01.507
‐ I'm sorry.

19:01.540 --> 19:03.142
‐ Good.

19:03.175 --> 19:06.646
Now I...do not accept
your apology!

19:06.679 --> 19:08.981
‐ Well, you‐‐
you have to accept it.

19:09.015 --> 19:10.149
‐ Why?

19:10.182 --> 19:12.151
‐ Those are the rules.

19:12.184 --> 19:16.489
‐ Well, he's not really sorry,
so I'm not accepting it.

19:16.522 --> 19:17.923
‐ Dr. Vanderspeigle is right.

19:17.957 --> 19:19.392
Max...

19:19.425 --> 19:21.193
say it like you mean it.

19:21.227 --> 19:22.495
‐ But I don't mean it!

19:22.528 --> 19:24.130
Your act
doesn't fool me, alien.

19:24.163 --> 19:26.298
I know you found us
in your basement

19:26.332 --> 19:27.767
and somehow snuck us home.

19:27.800 --> 19:30.736
‐ I'm feeling attacked.
I am snowflaking.

19:30.770 --> 19:31.871
‐ Max, that's‐‐that's enough.

19:31.904 --> 19:34.507
‐ Do you see what we're dealing
with, Dr. Vanderspeigle?

19:34.540 --> 19:37.009
[stammers]
He just won't let up.

19:37.043 --> 19:38.678
‐ I have an idea.

19:38.711 --> 19:41.147
They obviously love this kid.

19:41.180 --> 19:43.215
I'm not sure why.

19:43.249 --> 19:44.884
He's a menace.

19:44.917 --> 19:47.653
I learned a lesson from Asta
about love.

19:47.687 --> 19:50.456
It can be used as a weapon.

19:50.489 --> 19:51.857
Okay, Max.

19:51.891 --> 19:54.026
I'm going to give you
a simple test.

19:54.060 --> 19:58.564
Which one of these people...
is me?

19:58.597 --> 19:59.999
‐ You know I can't tell
by this.

20:00.032 --> 20:01.867
If there was a picture
of a gross alien

20:01.901 --> 20:04.270
or a dumb slug,
I'd point to it.

20:04.303 --> 20:05.538
‐ Hurtful.
‐ Max.

20:05.571 --> 20:07.006
Please stop fooling around.

20:07.039 --> 20:08.240
This is serious.

20:08.274 --> 20:09.742
‐ Fine.

20:09.775 --> 20:11.210
This one!
‐ No!

20:11.243 --> 20:13.713
Enough games, buddy.
That's Russell Crowe.

20:13.746 --> 20:14.780
‐ No, that's Sam Neill.

20:14.814 --> 20:16.015
‐ No, the Australian guy

20:16.048 --> 20:17.616
from the genius movie
with the math.

20:17.650 --> 20:19.251
‐ No, I promise you, it's not‐‐
‐ Hey!

20:19.285 --> 20:21.387
Snap out of it!

20:21.420 --> 20:22.955
Max got it wrong.

20:22.988 --> 20:25.991
‐ [sighs]
Sweetie, who is this?

20:26.025 --> 20:28.394
Don't you recognize him?
‐ No!

20:28.427 --> 20:31.263
I've never seen that man before
in my entire life.

20:31.297 --> 20:32.665
‐ Hmm, I forgive you

20:32.698 --> 20:34.400
for breaking
into my house, Max.

20:34.433 --> 20:35.768
I forgive you

20:35.801 --> 20:39.605
because you are
a sick little boy.

20:39.638 --> 20:42.208
And she's right.
It's Sam Neill!

20:42.241 --> 20:45.377
From the Jurassic‐era
dinosaur documentary!

20:45.411 --> 20:46.912
I‐‐
‐ He's lying!

20:46.946 --> 20:48.814
He's setting me up!
He's tricking you!

20:48.848 --> 20:50.249
‐ Hey‐‐
‐ He's not even a real doctor!

20:50.282 --> 20:52.618
‐ Max.
‐ Well, this has been fun.

20:52.651 --> 20:55.087
I'm just gonna go
jump out a window real quick.

20:55.121 --> 20:56.088
Max.

20:56.122 --> 20:58.324
‐ [sighs]

20:58.357 --> 21:00.793
‐ It's worse than I thought.

21:00.826 --> 21:02.628
He obviously suffers

21:02.661 --> 21:05.664
from a severe case
of teraphobia.

21:05.698 --> 21:06.899
‐ Teraphobia?

21:06.932 --> 21:10.336
‐ Seeing monsters
and other scary things.

21:10.369 --> 21:14.106
If you worry about one thing,
it should be that.

21:14.140 --> 21:16.242
Also...

21:16.275 --> 21:19.245
he might suffer
from face blindness

21:19.278 --> 21:22.448
and anxiety...

21:22.481 --> 21:24.950
and looking at your skull...

21:24.984 --> 21:27.753
he's probably gonna have
a receding hairline.

21:27.787 --> 21:28.988
‐ This is horrible.

21:29.021 --> 21:30.856
‐ If teraphobia
is untreated,

21:30.890 --> 21:33.392
Max can have severe issues,

21:33.425 --> 21:36.228
and going through life
without hair is no fun.

21:36.262 --> 21:37.730
But...

21:37.763 --> 21:41.634
there is a special school

21:41.667 --> 21:43.769
for kids like Max...

21:43.803 --> 21:45.638
in Georgia.

21:45.671 --> 21:46.806
‐ Georgia?
‐ Mm.

21:46.839 --> 21:49.775
[inquisitive music]

21:49.809 --> 21:51.677
♪ ♪

21:56.882 --> 21:57.383
‐ We just need a smoking gun.

21:58.884 --> 22:01.487
We ain't got no smoke.
Hell, we ain't even got a gun.

22:01.520 --> 22:02.955
[object whirring]

22:02.988 --> 22:05.191
I interviewed
every possible witness,

22:05.224 --> 22:07.960
and I examined
all the evidence. I‐‐

22:07.993 --> 22:09.795
Are you shitting me
right now?

22:09.829 --> 22:11.497
Are you playing with a yo‐yo?

22:11.530 --> 22:13.666
‐ Sorry, sir.
It, uh‐‐it calms me.

22:13.699 --> 22:16.135
‐ Well, I need to be calm.
Give me this.

22:18.304 --> 22:19.872
‐ Ow.

22:22.007 --> 22:24.176
‐ Got no viable suspects.

22:24.210 --> 22:26.378
We got no motive.
We got nothing!

22:26.412 --> 22:28.280
Hell, we don't even know
for sure yet

22:28.314 --> 22:30.216
if he was even murdered!

22:34.220 --> 22:36.488
[yo‐yo clatters]

22:36.522 --> 22:38.824
Great, you broke it.

22:38.858 --> 22:41.994
‐ Sir, Sam doesn't seem
the suicide type.

22:42.027 --> 22:44.496
I think he was murdered,
and I really do think

22:44.530 --> 22:46.365
it's somehow related
to the foot in the lake.

22:46.398 --> 22:48.000
‐ You know what?
Screw that foot.

22:48.033 --> 22:50.069
For all we know,
that thing floated downriver

22:50.102 --> 22:50.936
from up north.

22:50.970 --> 22:52.905
There's probably
some one‐footed sumbitch

22:52.938 --> 22:54.540
up in Gunnison, hopping around,

22:54.573 --> 22:56.408
laughing at our asses
right now.

22:56.442 --> 22:58.944
‐ Mm.
I don't think he laughs much.

23:01.046 --> 23:03.415
‐ I was so happy when I thought
we had a serial killer.

23:03.449 --> 23:05.050
It felt good.

23:05.084 --> 23:07.887
I mean,
look at these streets!

23:07.920 --> 23:10.856
They're not mean!
They're beautiful!

23:10.890 --> 23:12.157
You know how many
violent crimes

23:12.191 --> 23:14.994
Colorado Springs
had last year, hmm?

23:15.027 --> 23:16.996
Over 500.

23:17.029 --> 23:18.197
500!

23:18.230 --> 23:21.200
Lucky bastards.

23:21.233 --> 23:24.003
‐ Cheer up, sir.
Tomorrow is bingo night.

23:24.036 --> 23:27.072
Maybe Mrs. Labelle will
sucker‐punch the priest again.

23:27.106 --> 23:29.375
‐ Yeah, she is crazier
than zucchini cake.

23:29.408 --> 23:30.576
‐ Yeah.

23:30.609 --> 23:32.378
Actually, s‐she is my aunt.

23:32.411 --> 23:35.114
‐ Okay. Still shouldn't
put vegetables in cake.

23:36.482 --> 23:38.651
It's wrong.

23:38.684 --> 23:40.419
‐ We're smart, attractive...
‐ Yes. Mm!

23:40.452 --> 23:41.387
‐ Independent women.

23:41.420 --> 23:43.222
We don't need some guy
to determine our future.

23:43.255 --> 23:45.057
‐ We are strong!

23:45.090 --> 23:46.825
‐ We're strong.
And we're fearless!

23:46.859 --> 23:47.960
‐ You are fearless!

23:47.993 --> 23:49.361
‐ [sighs]
Damn right.

23:49.395 --> 23:51.063
‐ Except about this guy.

23:51.096 --> 23:53.732
I think you broke up with him

23:53.766 --> 23:55.734
because you were afraid
of getting hurt.

23:55.768 --> 23:57.903
‐ Mm. You think so?

23:57.937 --> 23:59.772
'Cause I thought it was
'cause he kissed like a horse

23:59.805 --> 24:00.973
eating an ice cream cone.

24:01.006 --> 24:03.108
‐ [laughing]

24:03.142 --> 24:04.843
I'm so sorry.

24:04.877 --> 24:07.813
Any real man
would be in love with you.

24:07.846 --> 24:09.782
‐ Yeah.
‐ Take it from an artist.

24:09.815 --> 24:11.483
Without risk, there's nothing.

24:11.517 --> 24:12.618
‐ Yeah.

24:12.651 --> 24:14.453
‐ Real women don't run away.

24:14.486 --> 24:15.621
‐ That's right.
‐ Mm!

24:15.654 --> 24:17.189
‐ We don't run away.
‐ Mm!

24:17.222 --> 24:20.392
‐ Because we're strong
because we support each other.

24:20.426 --> 24:21.760
‐ Right.

24:21.794 --> 24:23.062
‐ Have you seen Danny?

24:23.095 --> 24:25.431
‐ Day Drunk Danny that fixes
the karaoke machine?

24:25.464 --> 24:26.465
Jesus, Judy.

24:26.498 --> 24:27.900
‐ You're just jealous
I got a guy

24:27.933 --> 24:29.335
who can work in tight spaces.

24:29.368 --> 24:30.169
‐ Like you have any.

24:30.202 --> 24:31.804
‐ Oh, wouldn't you
like to know?

24:31.837 --> 24:33.339
‐ The whole town knows, Judy!

24:33.372 --> 24:35.207
‐ [laughs]

24:35.240 --> 24:36.809
I know.

24:36.842 --> 24:38.877
Hello.
‐ Hello.

24:40.079 --> 24:41.046
Pretty.

24:41.080 --> 24:42.715
‐ Hmm.

24:42.748 --> 24:44.650
‐ You guys!
‐ To women supporting women.

24:44.683 --> 24:46.185
‐ Yes.

24:47.853 --> 24:50.656
[door closes,
telephone ringing]

24:54.560 --> 24:55.928
‐ Hey, Jay.

24:55.961 --> 24:59.298
Thanks for picking up
the files.

24:59.331 --> 25:00.199
I know you like it here,

25:00.232 --> 25:02.901
and it's really been great
having you.

25:02.935 --> 25:05.371
Um, we're just...

25:05.404 --> 25:08.774
we're not as busy as we were
a couple months ago.

25:11.543 --> 25:13.712
Are you listening to me?

25:13.746 --> 25:17.049
‐ This paper says
you had a baby.

25:19.385 --> 25:22.788
And your baby was born
on my exact birthday.

25:23.789 --> 25:26.458
[somber music]

25:26.492 --> 25:27.659
It's fine.

25:27.693 --> 25:30.162
It's not like I didn't know
I was adopted.

25:30.195 --> 25:32.097
‐ I...

25:32.131 --> 25:34.333
It's...

25:34.366 --> 25:36.168
it's complicated.

25:37.736 --> 25:39.538
‐ You know...

25:39.571 --> 25:42.574
it seems simple.

25:42.608 --> 25:45.277
You gave me away
and then lied to me.

25:45.310 --> 25:49.114
♪ ♪

25:49.148 --> 25:50.716
Wait.

25:50.749 --> 25:54.486
If you're "Mommy,"
who's "Daddy"?

25:54.520 --> 25:56.588
It's not that dick Jimmy,
is it?

25:56.622 --> 26:01.126
♪ ♪

26:01.160 --> 26:03.762
Wow.

26:03.796 --> 26:06.565
I really won the lottery
with that one, didn't I?

26:06.598 --> 26:08.200
No wonder you gave me away.

26:08.233 --> 26:09.968
‐ I'm so sorry‐‐
‐ Don't.

26:10.002 --> 26:14.206
♪ ♪

26:14.239 --> 26:16.575
‐ I was going to fire her.

26:16.608 --> 26:23.482
♪ ♪

26:35.060 --> 26:37.229
Are you waiting for a bus?

26:37.262 --> 26:39.198
‐ I like the cold.
It helps me think.

26:40.766 --> 26:43.902
‐ Buddhist monks
believe that suffering

26:43.969 --> 26:47.106
comes from the thinking mind.

26:47.139 --> 26:49.808
They can also train their minds
not to feel pain.

26:49.842 --> 26:52.578
One of them
lit himself on fire.

26:52.611 --> 26:55.547
I think that one felt pain.

26:55.581 --> 26:56.949
‐ Trying to make me feel better

26:56.982 --> 26:59.284
after tearing the heart
out of a 17‐year‐old girl?

26:59.318 --> 27:01.153
‐ You didn't tear
her heart out.

27:01.186 --> 27:03.922
You just lied to her
and pretended to be her friend.

27:03.956 --> 27:06.091
‐ You want to talk about lying?

27:06.125 --> 27:10.329
What kind of person lies
about their wife being dead?

27:10.362 --> 27:12.631
‐ Humans lie.

27:12.664 --> 27:14.933
It's what they do.

27:16.268 --> 27:17.269
‐ Why?

27:19.037 --> 27:21.106
‐ Maybe they don't want
people to know

27:21.140 --> 27:24.309
who they really are.

27:24.343 --> 27:25.878
‐ Hmm.

27:25.911 --> 27:31.016
♪ ♪

27:32.217 --> 27:34.153
‐ I told you I'd meet you
at the diner.

27:34.186 --> 27:36.021
‐ Nice to see you, too.

27:37.990 --> 27:41.293
‐ Harry Vanderspeigle.
I think we met briefly.

27:41.326 --> 27:43.695
‐ Are you ‐‐‐‐‐‐‐ with me, man?

27:43.729 --> 27:45.797
‐ No, of course not.

27:45.831 --> 27:49.635
Chicken‐ass bitch.

27:49.668 --> 27:51.670
‐ Okay. Let's go.

27:51.703 --> 27:53.438
Let's go!

27:53.472 --> 27:56.508
[dramatic music]

27:56.542 --> 27:59.344
♪ ♪

27:59.378 --> 28:00.379
‐ [chuckles]

28:00.412 --> 28:01.847
[quiet music playing
on jukebox]

28:01.880 --> 28:03.182
‐ Don't.

28:03.215 --> 28:04.683
That is not why I texted you.

28:04.716 --> 28:06.451
‐ [chuckles]

28:06.485 --> 28:08.187
You always say that.

28:08.220 --> 28:11.056
‐ I need you to listen.

28:11.089 --> 28:13.992
This is hard.
It's about the baby.

28:15.160 --> 28:16.895
She found out who we are.

28:16.929 --> 28:19.698
♪ ♪

28:19.731 --> 28:21.400
‐ Whoa.

28:23.468 --> 28:25.537
How did she find you?

28:27.906 --> 28:29.508
‐ It's Jay.

28:29.541 --> 28:32.578
‐ The girl with the attitude
that answers the phone?

28:32.611 --> 28:34.213
‐ Yeah. She's our daughter.

28:34.246 --> 28:36.582
And, yes, I knew that
when I hired her.

28:36.615 --> 28:38.383
‐ Jesus, Asta.

28:38.417 --> 28:39.952
That is messed up.

28:39.985 --> 28:42.888
♪ ♪

28:42.921 --> 28:44.856
[sighs]

28:44.890 --> 28:48.760
♪ ♪

28:48.794 --> 28:50.028
What the hell is he doing here?

28:50.062 --> 28:52.164
What, is he your new boyfriend
or something?

28:52.197 --> 28:54.733
‐ No.
‐ No.

28:54.766 --> 28:57.035
I'm just here eating cake.

28:57.069 --> 28:58.737
‐ You her bodyguard now?
‐ Harry.

28:58.770 --> 29:00.472
‐ I prefer ninja.
‐ Harry.

29:00.505 --> 29:02.741
You don't have to do this.
Just ignore him.

29:02.774 --> 29:05.077
‐ You shouldn't ignore ninjas.

29:05.110 --> 29:06.478
‐ Just don't pay
any attention to him.

29:06.511 --> 29:09.581
He's reading books
about monks and ninjas.

29:09.615 --> 29:12.618
♪ ♪

29:12.651 --> 29:14.753
‐ How long have you known?

29:14.786 --> 29:16.788
‐ Always.

29:16.822 --> 29:19.057
Since you talked me
into giving up my own baby.

29:19.091 --> 29:20.525
‐ [pounds table]
Damn it, Asta!

29:20.559 --> 29:21.793
You weren't ready either!

29:21.827 --> 29:23.528
‐ Are you serious?

29:23.562 --> 29:26.898
♪ ♪

29:26.932 --> 29:29.901
I'm only telling you so that
you will hear it from me first.

29:29.935 --> 29:32.070
If Jay comes to find you,

29:32.104 --> 29:33.472
I don't want you
flipping out on her.

29:33.505 --> 29:35.073
You're the last person
she needs in her life.

29:35.107 --> 29:36.441
‐ Oh, right.

29:36.475 --> 29:38.510
You always make me out
to be the psycho.

29:38.543 --> 29:39.444
You know what?

29:39.478 --> 29:42.114
Doing what you did,
that shit ain't normal.

29:42.147 --> 29:43.548
You really wanted
to protect her,

29:43.582 --> 29:45.817
you should've stayed the hell
out of her life.

29:45.851 --> 29:49.788
♪ ♪

29:49.821 --> 29:53.191
[door opens, bell jingles]

29:53.225 --> 29:54.826
[door closes]

29:54.860 --> 29:57.362
♪ ♪

29:57.396 --> 29:59.097
‐ It's better that she knows.

29:59.131 --> 30:00.232
‐ This isn't your problem.

30:00.265 --> 30:02.367
You shouldn't have
to deal with it.

30:02.401 --> 30:05.771
‐ You're too young
to remember...

30:05.804 --> 30:09.474
but that night, when I realized
your mother wasn't coming back,

30:09.508 --> 30:13.312
I tucked you in extra tight,
and I made a promise to you

30:13.345 --> 30:16.214
that I'd never leave you
to do this life alone.

30:17.849 --> 30:19.851
‐ How could I leave her?

30:19.885 --> 30:22.020
‐ Well, you didn't know
any better.

30:22.054 --> 30:24.189
But I promise you,
she has a family

30:24.222 --> 30:27.626
that loves her
as if she was their own.

30:27.659 --> 30:33.999
♪ ♪

30:34.032 --> 30:35.801
‐ Where did Harry go?

30:35.834 --> 30:38.003
[Harry clears throat]

30:38.036 --> 30:39.604
‐ Ninja.

30:44.576 --> 30:44.943
[suspenseful music]

30:47.179 --> 30:50.949
♪ ♪

30:50.982 --> 30:54.186
[truck door closes]

30:54.219 --> 30:56.688
‐ Why is she still here?

30:56.722 --> 30:58.724
How am I supposed to get
into my underwear

30:58.757 --> 31:02.494
and watch Jerry Orbach
with that hot ham in my house?

31:02.527 --> 31:05.497
[Luíza Boê's "Cocoon"
playing on radio]

31:05.530 --> 31:08.633
[Luíza singing in Portuguese]

31:08.667 --> 31:15.574
♪ ♪

31:20.145 --> 31:22.481
You said you were
going away forever.

31:23.782 --> 31:26.752
‐ I'm afraid I didn't handle
things very well today.

31:26.785 --> 31:29.087
I'd really love
to make it up to you.

31:29.121 --> 31:30.655
Hope you're hungry.

31:30.689 --> 31:32.958
♪ ♪

31:32.991 --> 31:34.626
‐ Where did you
get these steaks?

31:34.659 --> 31:37.763
‐ They were in the freezer
downstairs.

31:37.796 --> 31:42.000
‐ That's impossible,
because the door is...

31:42.033 --> 31:43.969
[shrieks]
Open!

31:44.002 --> 31:45.470
‐ You freak, I don't know why

31:45.504 --> 31:47.305
you locked everything
like that.

31:47.339 --> 31:48.573
I don't think we have
to do that out here.

31:48.607 --> 31:50.142
I had to break the lock
of the icebox

31:50.175 --> 31:52.210
just to get the...steaks.

31:52.244 --> 31:54.413
Got to get some frozen peas.

31:55.313 --> 31:57.215
‐ I'll get them.

31:59.117 --> 32:00.685
‐ You're lovely.

32:00.719 --> 32:05.357
♪ ♪

32:05.390 --> 32:08.393
[suspenseful music]

32:08.427 --> 32:10.128
♪ ♪

32:10.162 --> 32:12.030
‐ [grunts]

32:12.063 --> 32:19.137
♪ ♪

32:30.348 --> 32:33.985
[romantic music
playing on radio]

32:34.019 --> 32:35.687
Mmm.

32:35.720 --> 32:37.823
‐ You're so quiet.
What are you thinking?

32:37.856 --> 32:39.825
‐ If I could fit your body
in the freezer

32:39.858 --> 32:41.092
next to the other guy.

32:41.126 --> 32:43.261
So many things.

32:44.863 --> 32:47.365
‐ You're so different.

32:47.399 --> 32:49.768
You haven't been yourself
since I got here.

32:49.801 --> 32:51.803
‐ I am myself.

32:51.837 --> 32:54.473
I've always been myself.

32:54.506 --> 32:56.208
A man...

32:56.241 --> 32:59.478
and nothing else.

32:59.511 --> 33:02.047
‐ See, that's what
I'm talking about.

33:02.080 --> 33:03.915
I know what's going on
with you.

33:05.717 --> 33:07.819
You're afraid.

33:07.853 --> 33:09.321
‐ I'll go with that.

33:09.354 --> 33:11.256
‐ I'm scared, too.

33:11.289 --> 33:12.691
Men showed up at the apartment

33:12.724 --> 33:14.726
and said they needed
to talk to you.

33:14.759 --> 33:16.394
Look, I don't care
what trouble you're in.

33:16.428 --> 33:18.129
I really don't.

33:18.163 --> 33:20.232
Whatever's going on with you,

33:20.265 --> 33:22.100
I'll be there with you,
no matter what.

33:22.133 --> 33:29.207
♪ ♪

33:42.387 --> 33:44.055
‐ All right, D'arce.

33:44.089 --> 33:45.924
You want to put yourself
out there?

33:51.463 --> 33:53.999
Let's do this.

33:54.032 --> 33:56.468
‐ Come on, you beast.
Let's have a dance.

33:56.501 --> 33:59.638
[Kat Edmonson's "If" playing
on radio]

33:59.671 --> 34:00.839
♪ ♪

34:00.872 --> 34:05.911
‐ ♪ If you're going home
one evening ♪

34:05.944 --> 34:07.379
♪ And you... ♪

34:07.412 --> 34:10.315
[song continues muffled]

34:10.348 --> 34:17.489
♪ ♪

34:18.823 --> 34:20.825
‐ [sighs]
Shit.

34:20.859 --> 34:23.361
♪ ♪

34:23.395 --> 34:25.830
That was a waste of deodorant.

34:25.864 --> 34:32.771
♪ ♪

34:37.442 --> 34:40.211
‐ Well, dinner's over.

34:40.245 --> 34:41.646
‐ Mm.

34:41.680 --> 34:43.481
‐ What next?

34:44.816 --> 34:47.319
‐ I can only think
of one thing.

34:47.352 --> 34:49.287
‐ Hmm?

34:49.321 --> 34:51.656
‐ Scrub the pans
before you leave.

34:56.394 --> 35:00.532
‐ ♪ There was a boy ♪

35:00.565 --> 35:03.902
♪ A very strange ♪

35:03.969 --> 35:07.939
♪ Enchanted boy ♪

35:07.973 --> 35:11.343
♪ They say he wandered
very far ♪

35:12.844 --> 35:16.181
♪ Very far ♪

35:16.214 --> 35:20.652
♪ Over land and sea ♪

35:20.685 --> 35:23.321
♪ And then one day ♪

35:23.355 --> 35:27.325
♪ One magic day,
he passed my way ♪

35:27.359 --> 35:31.997
♪ And while we spoke
of many things ♪

35:32.030 --> 35:36.167
♪ Fools and kings ♪

35:36.201 --> 35:40.605
♪ This he said to me ♪

35:42.974 --> 35:47.712
♪ The greatest thing
you'll ever learn ♪

35:49.347 --> 35:52.183
♪ Is to love ♪

35:52.217 --> 35:55.420
♪ And be loved ♪

35:55.453 --> 35:58.890
♪ Just to love ♪

35:58.923 --> 36:02.260
♪ And be ♪

36:02.293 --> 36:06.264
♪ Loved ♪

36:06.297 --> 36:07.565
‐ Well...

36:07.599 --> 36:10.468
[slow romantic music]

36:10.502 --> 36:12.671
♪ ♪

36:12.704 --> 36:14.272
Mm.

36:14.305 --> 36:21.379
♪ ♪

36:31.723 --> 36:33.725
‐ You want to send him
to Georgia?

36:33.758 --> 36:36.227
‐ Of course I don't want
to send him away.

36:36.261 --> 36:38.697
But we have a broken child.

36:40.098 --> 36:42.033
The only thing scarier
than being away from him

36:42.067 --> 36:44.002
is him getting worse if we
don't do something about it.

36:44.035 --> 36:46.037
‐ But maybe he'll outgrow it
on his own.

36:46.071 --> 36:47.772
You know, like the lisp
or the‐‐or the thumb sucking.

36:47.806 --> 36:49.040
‐ No.
‐ I just‐‐I think‐‐

36:49.074 --> 36:50.542
I just think that we should
give it more time.

36:50.575 --> 36:51.776
‐ This is different.

36:51.810 --> 36:53.378
This place is equipped
to help him

36:53.411 --> 36:55.914
in ways that we can't.

36:55.947 --> 36:56.881
Be honest.

36:56.915 --> 37:00.952
Does Max seem like a normal
little boy to you?

37:04.122 --> 37:06.458
‐ No, I‐I guess not.

37:06.491 --> 37:08.460
[somber music]

37:08.493 --> 37:10.095
‐ Am I losing my hair?

37:10.128 --> 37:11.863
‐ What? No. What?

37:11.896 --> 37:15.200
‐ Don't you feel like
it's gone back a little bit?

37:15.233 --> 37:16.768
‐ No.

37:16.801 --> 37:20.805
‐ Max for Sahar.
Do you read me?

37:20.839 --> 37:22.941
‐ Sahar here, over.
[walkie‐talkie chirps]

37:22.974 --> 37:25.443
‐ I know you don't believe me
about the alien.

37:25.477 --> 37:28.313
My parents are sending me away.

37:28.346 --> 37:29.614
Over.

37:29.647 --> 37:32.250
‐ All I said was that
I didn't remember.

37:32.283 --> 37:33.952
Of course I still believe you.

37:33.985 --> 37:35.854
And nobody's sending you away.

37:35.887 --> 37:37.722
I have an idea. Over.

37:40.592 --> 37:43.561
[mischievous music]

37:43.595 --> 37:45.563
♪ ♪

37:45.597 --> 37:48.099
‐ [French accent] There's
no need to be frightened.

37:48.133 --> 37:49.367
[laughs]

37:49.400 --> 37:50.802
I'll take care of you.

37:50.835 --> 37:52.904
Tell Babette where it hurts.

37:52.937 --> 37:54.739
‐ I don't know who Babette is‐‐

37:54.773 --> 37:56.808
[moans]
‐ [chuckles]

37:56.841 --> 37:59.778
‐ Ooh, that feels good.
[laughs, moans]

37:59.811 --> 38:02.413
‐ ♪ I like it like that ♪

38:02.447 --> 38:04.849
[moaning]

38:04.883 --> 38:09.788
‐ ♪ You got me yearning,
burning with desire ♪

38:09.821 --> 38:12.924
‐ [grunting]
‐ [laughing]

38:12.957 --> 38:14.559
‐ ♪ You drive me wild ♪

38:14.592 --> 38:15.693
‐ God, you're handsome.

38:15.727 --> 38:17.061
‐ So are you.
‐ [laughs]

38:17.095 --> 38:18.596
‐ ♪ Have mercy, Mr. Percy ♪

38:18.630 --> 38:20.965
♪ Now, cut that out ♪

38:20.999 --> 38:22.634
‐ [moans]

38:22.667 --> 38:25.069
I don't know
what we're doing.

38:25.103 --> 38:26.271
‐ We're reconnecting.

38:26.304 --> 38:27.472
‐ Oh‐‐oh.

38:27.505 --> 38:29.474
[moaning]

38:29.507 --> 38:30.875
‐ ♪ Cha, cha‐cha‐cha, cha ♪

38:30.909 --> 38:31.709
‐ Oh!

38:31.743 --> 38:34.879
[rasping cries]

38:37.715 --> 38:40.084
‐ ♪ I like it like that ♪

38:40.118 --> 38:41.486
♪ ♪

38:41.519 --> 38:43.988
‐ ♪ Cha ♪
‐ ♪ I like it like that ♪

38:44.022 --> 38:45.790
‐ ♪ Cha, cha‐cha‐cha, cha ♪

38:45.824 --> 38:48.226
‐ ♪ I like it, I like it ♪

38:51.329 --> 38:53.531
[birds chirping]

38:53.565 --> 38:56.367
‐ [sighs]
I knew you still loved me.

38:56.401 --> 38:58.336
Didn't have the heart
to take it down.

38:58.369 --> 39:00.405
[serene music]

39:00.438 --> 39:02.307
[sighs] We're gonna be
together forever.

39:02.340 --> 39:09.514
♪ ♪

39:14.352 --> 39:14.686
[indistinct chatter]

39:17.021 --> 39:20.124
[door opens, bell jingles]

39:20.158 --> 39:24.429
[pop music playing
on jukebox]

39:24.462 --> 39:27.432
‐ I thought you'd be in Georgia
by now getting probed.

39:27.465 --> 39:31.135
‐ Humans don't probe.
Only stupid aliens do that.

39:31.169 --> 39:33.004
[door opens, bell jingles]
‐ My people don't.

39:33.037 --> 39:34.973
It's the greys
that have the ass fetish.

39:35.006 --> 39:37.909
‐ That's adult language,
and we don't appreciate it.

39:37.942 --> 39:39.811
‐ What are you doing here?

39:39.844 --> 39:41.079
‐ You shouldn't be
that surprised to see me.

39:41.112 --> 39:43.882
Touching your floating apple
may have knocked out my memory,

39:43.915 --> 39:45.950
but it didn't kill me.

39:45.984 --> 39:47.819
‐ Maybe next time.

39:47.852 --> 39:49.954
‐ There won't be a next time.

39:49.988 --> 39:52.957
‐ Hold on, Max.
The adults are talking.

39:52.991 --> 39:55.159
Max isn't going
to that institute.

39:55.193 --> 39:57.161
I once held my breath
for two minutes

39:57.195 --> 40:00.365
just to get out
of a Sufi prayer circle.

40:00.398 --> 40:02.166
I'll teach him.

40:02.200 --> 40:03.835
I'll bet he'll hold his breath
for an hour

40:03.868 --> 40:05.069
to get out of Georgia.

40:05.103 --> 40:06.437
‐ Good.
Then he'll be dead.

40:06.471 --> 40:09.240
I'll find his tombstone
and spit on it.

40:09.274 --> 40:10.608
‐ You won't be able to

40:10.642 --> 40:12.310
because he's going
to be cremated

40:12.343 --> 40:15.113
and have the ashes sprinkled
into the ocean.

40:15.146 --> 40:19.317
‐ Fine. Then I'll spit on it,
and it'll hit your dead DNA.

40:19.350 --> 40:21.352
‐ No, it won't.
Because I tricked you.

40:21.386 --> 40:24.122
He didn't really have his ashes
put into the ocean.

40:24.155 --> 40:26.357
I snuck them into your pocket.

40:26.391 --> 40:28.493
So, when you were spitting
into the ocean,

40:28.526 --> 40:32.230
he was in your pocket
laughing at you the whole time.

40:32.263 --> 40:34.766
Your spit will never
get near him.

40:34.799 --> 40:36.434
‐ We win again.

40:36.467 --> 40:38.102
‐ [spits]

40:38.136 --> 40:40.271
Ha ha!
I got you.

40:42.173 --> 40:43.608
[chuckles]

40:43.641 --> 40:46.344
♪ ♪

40:46.377 --> 40:48.780
I don't think
what I just did was...

40:48.813 --> 40:50.515
normal human behavior.

40:50.548 --> 40:53.384
‐ Oh. Are we driving you crazy?

40:53.418 --> 40:54.852
Get used to it.

40:54.886 --> 40:56.854
We're both holding our breath
until you promise

40:56.888 --> 40:58.990
to leave him alone.

40:59.023 --> 41:03.394
When we pass out,
they'll think you did it.

41:03.428 --> 41:05.530
[both inhale deeply]

41:05.563 --> 41:08.366
‐ Good. It'll be quieter.

41:08.399 --> 41:15.006
♪ ♪

41:15.039 --> 41:17.375
Great. More air for me.

41:17.408 --> 41:19.711
[exaggerated breathing]

41:19.744 --> 41:21.012
Thank you.
I'll have some more.

41:21.045 --> 41:24.415
[exaggerated breathing]

41:24.449 --> 41:26.751
♪ ♪

41:26.784 --> 41:28.386
You look silly.

41:30.121 --> 41:32.824
Look, I mean,
how long is this?

41:34.692 --> 41:36.961
Okay.

41:36.995 --> 41:38.296
Okay, stop!

41:38.329 --> 41:40.264
[both gasping]

41:40.298 --> 41:41.399
‐ [coughs]

41:41.432 --> 41:43.735
‐ What do you want?
‐ A truce.

41:43.768 --> 41:45.503
You tell my parents
I'm not crazy

41:45.536 --> 41:46.838
so I can stay home,

41:46.871 --> 41:48.873
and I'll stop telling everyone
you're an alien.

41:48.906 --> 41:51.242
‐ What about killing him?
Can I still kill him?

41:51.275 --> 41:52.877
‐ No!

41:52.910 --> 41:55.446
That's pretty much implied
in the word "truce."

41:55.480 --> 41:57.849
‐ [grunts]

41:57.882 --> 41:59.917
‐ Go ahead.

41:59.951 --> 42:01.753
Shake on it.

42:01.786 --> 42:03.254
‐ Fine.

42:03.287 --> 42:06.891
♪ ♪

42:06.924 --> 42:08.526
‐ Any questions, Max?

42:08.559 --> 42:10.828
‐ Yeah. Why can I see you?

42:10.862 --> 42:13.498
‐ Are you familiar with
multidimensional space travel?

42:13.531 --> 42:14.832
‐ Very.

42:14.866 --> 42:16.434
‐ Some humans
are genetically more tuned

42:16.467 --> 42:18.169
to the frequencies
of other dimensions,

42:18.202 --> 42:20.204
so they can see beyond
my molecular reconstruction.

42:20.238 --> 42:22.340
‐ Like that was blue and black

42:22.373 --> 42:24.275
but some people saw it
as white and gold?

42:24.308 --> 42:25.576
both:
It wasn't white and gold?

42:25.610 --> 42:26.978
‐ No!

42:27.011 --> 42:28.880
‐ Whoa.
‐ Wow.

42:28.913 --> 42:31.282
‐ I have a question.

42:31.315 --> 42:34.986
Why do humans fold pizza
when they eat it?

42:35.019 --> 42:36.621
‐ Basic engineering.

42:36.654 --> 42:38.256
It's too floppy when it's flat.

42:38.289 --> 42:39.624
‐ Ah.

42:39.657 --> 42:41.059
‐ What are the Nazca lines?

42:41.092 --> 42:43.461
‐ Ancient alien graffiti.

42:43.494 --> 42:44.796
‐ Do aliens poop?

42:44.829 --> 42:45.963
‐ Everybody poops.

42:45.997 --> 42:47.231
[both laugh]

42:47.265 --> 42:49.901
‐ Just like the book.
I knew it.

42:49.934 --> 42:53.604
‐ When I first discovered that
Max knew who I really was,

42:53.638 --> 42:55.339
I hated him for it.

42:55.373 --> 42:57.942
[Raye Zaragoza's
"American Dream"]

42:57.975 --> 43:00.344
Maybe I did not
actually hate him.

43:02.146 --> 43:05.416
I just hated
how he made me feel inside.

43:05.450 --> 43:09.387
[car doors close]
I felt exposed, vulnerable.

43:09.420 --> 43:11.823
In a way, I hated myself.

43:11.856 --> 43:15.760
‐ ♪ I've been thinking
about the news ♪

43:15.793 --> 43:20.264
♪ Daddy leaves it on
all day through ♪

43:20.298 --> 43:23.868
♪ I've been thinking
about the wars ♪

43:23.901 --> 43:27.105
♪ And to be honest
I can't take anymore ♪

43:27.138 --> 43:31.843
♪ I hear you every day ♪

43:31.876 --> 43:35.947
♪ The awful words you say ♪

43:35.980 --> 43:37.682
♪ But hate can't be ♪

43:37.715 --> 43:42.019
♪ The face
of the American Dream ♪

43:42.053 --> 43:46.591
♪ ♪

43:46.624 --> 43:48.292
‐ But after talking
to those kids

43:48.326 --> 43:51.129
for just ten minutes,

43:51.162 --> 43:53.698
I could feel my hatred
going away.

43:53.731 --> 43:56.267
♪ ♪

43:56.300 --> 44:00.505
Maybe there's something
out there stronger than hate.

44:00.538 --> 44:02.073
‐ Hungry?

44:02.106 --> 44:03.908
‐ I've only got enough
for coffee.

44:03.941 --> 44:05.176
‐ Well, that's okay.

44:05.209 --> 44:06.544
Family don't pay.

44:06.577 --> 44:09.080
♪ ♪

44:09.113 --> 44:11.716
‐ In that case,
I'll get two burgers‐‐

44:11.749 --> 44:12.884
one for here and one to go‐‐

44:12.917 --> 44:15.720
and a slice of pie.

44:15.753 --> 44:17.054
‐ Yeah, all right.

44:17.088 --> 44:21.592
♪ ♪

44:21.626 --> 44:22.727
‐ Sheriff?

44:22.760 --> 44:24.829
♪ ♪

44:24.862 --> 44:27.098
Sam's toxicology results
are in.

44:27.131 --> 44:29.867
Botulinum toxin A levels
are through the roof.

44:29.901 --> 44:31.536
Sam was poisoned.

44:31.569 --> 44:34.939
‐ Holy shit sticks!
We got ourselves a murder!

44:34.972 --> 44:39.510
[laughing]

44:39.544 --> 44:41.212
[clears throat]

44:41.245 --> 44:42.346
Deputy.
‐ Yeah. Sheriff.

44:42.380 --> 44:43.314
‐ All right. Get on it.
‐ Okay.

44:43.347 --> 44:45.016
‐ Get on it.
‐ Yeah. Enjoy your breakfast.

44:45.049 --> 44:47.151
‐ All right, thank you, ma'am.
‐ Okay.

44:47.185 --> 44:51.656
[Isabelle snoring]

44:51.689 --> 44:55.026
‐ I feel many emotions
about this one.

44:56.127 --> 44:58.262
I feel close to her.

44:58.296 --> 45:00.464
‐ ♪ And I been thinkin'
about our mother ♪

45:00.498 --> 45:03.034
‐ Yet sometimes,
I want to be far away.

45:03.067 --> 45:05.636
‐ ♪ How they took her away
from her people ♪

45:05.670 --> 45:07.171
[snoring stops]

45:07.205 --> 45:10.374
♪ Put her in
a boarding school ♪

45:10.408 --> 45:12.677
♪ Away from her brother,
sister, and culture ♪

45:12.710 --> 45:14.111
[snoring resumes]

45:14.145 --> 45:16.914
♪ I can hear her
every night ♪

45:16.948 --> 45:18.983
‐ I don't hate her.

45:19.016 --> 45:22.486
I just...need...sleep.

45:22.520 --> 45:24.522
‐ ♪ 'Cause hate can't be ♪

45:24.555 --> 45:28.326
♪ The face
of the American Dream ♪

45:28.359 --> 45:30.695
‐ I guess she can
live another day.

45:30.728 --> 45:34.732
‐ ♪ And change is a choice,
and it can start with you ♪
